The '''Pueblo linguistic area''' (or '''Pueblo Sprachbund''', '''Pueblo convergence area''') is a [[Sprachbund]] (group of languages with similarities due to [[language contact]]) consisting of the language spoken in and near North American [[Pueblo]] locations. There are also many [[Puebloan peoples|shared cultural practices]] in this area. For example, these cultures share many ceremonial vocabulary terms meant for prayer or song.{{sfn|Mithun|1999|p=318}}
==Language membership==
The languages of the linguistic area are the following:
* [[Zuni language]] * [[Tanoan languages|Tanoan family]] * [[Keresan language]] * [[Hopi language]] * [[Navajo language]]
The languages belong to five different families: Zuni, Tanoan, Keresan, [[Uto-Aztecan languages|Uto-Aztecan]] (Hopi), and [[Athabaskan languages|Athabaskan]] (Navajo, from the [[Apachean languages|Apachean subfamily]]). Zuni is a [[language isolate]]. Navajo is only a marginal member of the Sprachbund and does not share all its linguistic features, as the ancestors of the Navajo originated from Canada and Alaska and were relatively recent newcomers to the Southwest. Languages in the Tanoan and Apachean families, and additionally Hopi, can be compared to relatives not affected by this particular region's [[Areal feature|areal features]] as a reference for changes due to contact.{{sfn|Mithun|1999|p=318}}
Tanoan consists of [[Taos language|Taos]], [[Picurís language|Picurís]], [[Tewa language|Tewa]], and [[Towa language|Jemez]]. Keresan consists of Eastern Keres and Western Keres.<ref>Keresan (or Keres) has variously been considered as a small family of two languages or a single language of [[Dialect continuum|dialect chaining]].</ref>
==Shared linguistic traits and aereal features==
The following are the [[Areal feature|shared linguistic traits]] of the Pueblo Sprachbund:
* [[Tone (linguistics)|tones]], absent only in Zuni{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}} * SOV word order (though inherited from proto-languages in the case of Navajo [[Proto-Athabaskan]] and Hopi (Proto(-Northern)-Uto-Aztecan){{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}} * [[ejective]] [[consonant]]s {{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}} * [[Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]] consonants {{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}} * {{IPA|/i, e, a, o, u/}} [[vowel]] systems {{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}{{sfn|Sherzer|1976|p=133}} * final [[Voicelessness#Voiceless vowels and other sonorants|devoicing]] of vowels & [[sonorant]]s{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}} * [[Dual (grammatical number)|dual number]] * ceremonial vocabulary {{sfn|Mithun|1999|p=318}} * [[labialized]] [[velar]] [[Stop consonant|stops]] {{IPA|/kʷ, kʷʼ/}} {{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}
Most languages have ejectives. Zuni may have developed ejectives due to contact with Tanoan and Keresan which both have complete series of ejectives: Zuni has {{IPA|/tsʼ, tʃʼ, kʼ, kʷʼ/}} but lacks the ejectives {{IPA|/pʼ, tʼ/}} found in the other languages. Taos and Picurís (both Tanoan) have {{IPA|/pʼ, tʼ, tʃʼ, kʼ, kʷʼ/}}; Tewa (Tanoan) has {{IPA|/pʼ, tʼ, tsʼ, kʼ, kʷʼ/}}; Jemez (Tanoan) has {{IPA|/pʼ, tʼ, kʼ/}};<ref>In Jemez, Proto-Tanoan *c’ has merged with *t’ and *kʷ’ has merged with *kʷ explaining the lack of {{IPA|/tsʼ, kʷʼ/}} in Jemez that are found in other Tanoan languages.</ref> Keresan has {{IPA|/pʼ, tʼ, tsʼ, tʂʼ, tʃʼ, kʼ, sʼ, ʂʼ, ʃʼ/}} (as well as [[Glottalic consonant|glottalized]] [[sonorant]]s {{IPA|/mʼ, nʼ, rʼ, wʼ, jʼ/}}). Hopi lacks ejectives completely. Navajo has {{IPA|/tʼ, tsʼ, tɬʼ, tʃʼ, kʼ, kʷʼ/}}.<ref>The lack of {{IPA|/pʼ/}} in Navajo is an inheritance from [[Athabascan#Proto-Athabaskan|Proto-Athabascan]].</ref>
Navajo may have acquired the stop /kʷ/ <!-- Isn't this just a regular stop, not an ejective? --> from Puebloan contact.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}{{sfn|Sherzer|1976|p=151-152}} Sherzer suggests that contact led to Acoma Keres sharing glottalized sonorants and glides with Navajo.{{sfn|Sherzer|1976|p=137}}
Zuni may have obtained its partial glottalized set and aspirants via contact with Tanoan and Keresan, which both have fully integrated series of glottals.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}
Other shared traits include Santa Clara acquiring retroflex sounds from Keresan and the Navajo acquiring /hʷ/ from Tanoan contact.{{sfn|Mithun|1999|p=318}} Keresan may be the common source of glottalized nasals and semivowels in Navajo, and the development of /r/ in dialects of Tewa and Tiwa and possibly Hopi.{{sfn|Mithun|1999|p=318}}
Linguist [[Paul V. Kroskrity|Paul Kroskrity]] argues for diffused Apachean traits in Tewa, such as the [[Passive voice|passive]] marked by [[Prefix|prefixes]] that are structured differently from those of other Tanoan languages.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1982|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1985|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1993|p=60-66}} In these languages the verb is made [[Intransitive verb|intransitive]] by allowing an [[Agent (linguistics)|agent]] argument in the verb structure.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1982|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1985|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1993|p=60-66}} This also includes [[Patient (grammar)|patient subjects]] and cases where the subject must be [[Animacy|animate]], including raising animate objects to the place of inanimate subjects.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1982|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1985|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1993|p=60-66}} Further, Navajo and Tewa are the only languages in this group to have a "recognizable [[Anaphora (linguistics)|anaphor]] as a [[relativizer]]" when forming relative clauses.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1982|p=65}} Kroskrity also finds similarity in the Tewa [[Possessive affix|possessive suffix]] -bí, which parallels the third person possessive prefix bi- found in Apachean languages.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339-340}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1982|p=66}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1985|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1993|p=60-66}} This can be seen in the following example provided by Kroskrity:{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=340}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1982|p=66}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1985|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1993|p=60-66}}
{| class="wikitable" '''Diffused ''bi'' Morpheme''' |- ! Language !! Example !! [[Morpheme]] Analysis !! English [[Gloss (annotation)|Gloss]] |- | Arizona Tewa || sen-bí kʰaw || [man-POSS song] || '(a) man's song' |- | Navajo || bisóódi bi-tsi || [pig POSS-flesh] || 'the pig's flesh' |- |}
This paralleling morpheme is also used in these languages' postpositional constructions.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=340}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1982|p=66}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1985|}}{{sfn|Kroskrity|1993|p=60-66}} The reason for this diffusion<!-- All the diffusion or just this morpheme? --> has been attributed to trade networks and Apachean settlements near Pueblos in winter months.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=340}}
==Vowels== Sherzer suggests that the 2-2-1 vowel system found in Tanoan languages (i, e, a, o, u) may be a result of contact with Zuni and Keresan language families.{{sfn|Campbell|1997|p=339}} Sherzer states, "A 2-2-1 vowel system is a Pueblo-cintered regional areal trait. Its development in some Tanoan languages may be due to contact with Zuni and Keresan."{{sfn|Sherzer|1976|p=133}}
